PART 1 STATEMENT OF CURRENTLY-EFFECTIVE RATES
The following is a statement of the currently-effective maximum rates for gas transportation service provided by Columbia Gas of Kentucky, Inc. on its pipeline system under Section 311 of the Natural Gas Policy Act of 1978: DELIVERY SERVICE (DS)
Base Rate Charges:
Customer Charge
$3,982.30 per billing period
Volumetric Rate
First 30,000 Mcf $0.7093 per Mcf Next 70,000 Mcf $0.4378 per Mcf Over 100,000 Mcf $0.2423 per Mcf
State-Approved Adjustment Clause and Tracker (SAACT) Charges
Research and Development Rider (applicable to all volumes delivered)
$0.0124 per Mcf
SMRP Rider (applicable to all volumes delivered)
$0.0587 per Mcf
The foregoing SAACT charges fluctuate periodically in accordance with orders of the Kentucky Public Service Commission. These charges will be updated in this Statement of Operating Conditions whenever the cumulative increase in such charges exceeds ten percent (10%).
Banking and Balancing Service Charge (applicable to all volumes delivered)
$0.0362 per Mcf
Retainage
Retainage is based on the level of the Company’s system-wide lost and unaccounted-for gas. It is recalculated in December of each year, effective on January 1.
Reconnect Fee
$20.00
Late Payment Charge
A late payment penalty of five percent (5%) may be assessed only once on any bill for services rendered, if Shipper fails to pay the bill by the due date shown on the bill.
Returned Payment Fee
A charge of $14.00 will be assessed if a Shipper payment is returned by a bank as unpaid.
Charges for Shipper-Authorized Work
During Regular Working Hours $30.25 per hour for first employee $28.25 per hour for each additional employee, if needed One-hour minimum charge per employee of $30.25 Charges after first hour to nearest ¼ hour: $5.25 per quarter hour for first employee, $4.75 per quarter hour for each additional employee if needed
Work Outside Normal Working Hours including Holidays and Weekends $45.50 per hour for first employee; $42.50 per hour for each additional employee if needed. One-hour minimum charge per employee of $45.50. Charges after first hour to nearest ¼ hour: $8.00 per quarter hour for first employee; $7.25 per quarter hour for each additional employee, if needed
Work while Employee is on Premises Regular Working Hours: Charges to nearest ¼ hour: $5.25 per quarter hour for first employee; $4.75 per quarter hour for each additional employee, if needed Outside Regular Working Hours including Holidays and Weekends: Charges to nearest ¼ hour: $8.00 per quarter hour for first employee; $7.25 per quarter hour for each additional employee, if needed
Time Time for labor charges shall start at the time the actual Shipper-authorized work is started and end when the Shipper-authorized work is completed.
Inability to Gain Access Where special arrangements are made to do Shipper-authorized work and, upon arriving at the Shipper’s premises the Company employee cannot gain access to perform the previously scheduled work, a minimum one-hour charge, in effect for that time of day, may be made.
Material Charges Material charges shall consist of the following: 1) If the materials are available at the Company warehouse, the material charge will be the cost of the part plus a 35% markup. 2) If the materials are not available at the Company warehouse, the material charge will be billed to the Shipper at the invoice cost of the part plus a 10% markup and any applicable shipping charges.
Penalty for Failure to Interrupt Pursuant to Section 27 of Part 2 of this Statement of Operating Conditions
$25 per Mcf
Penalty for Excess Takes Under Section 28 of Part 2 of this Statement of Operating Conditions
$10 per Mcf
Penalty for Failure to Comply with Balancing Service Interruption (BSI)
$25 per Mcf for the BSI difference
PART 2 GENERAL TERMS AND CONDITIONS
Purpose and Effect This Statement of Operating Conditions contains the general terms and conditions under which Columbia Gas of Kentucky, Inc. (“the Company”) will provide NGPA Section 311 Gas Transportation Service in interstate commerce to qualifying shippers, including both end-users and suppliers of natural gas or renewable natural gas, under its Delivery Service (DS) rate schedule pursuant to the Blanket Certificate of Limited Jurisdiction issued by the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission (“FERC” or “Commission”). Section 1 – Definitions
Account includes all gas volumes which (1) are transported by the same individual, governmental, or corporate entity, including subsidiaries and affiliates, and (2) occurs on property which is either contiguous or is separated by no more than the width of a public or private right-of-way.
Annual Period means the twelve-month period beginning on the first day of Shipper’s November billing cycle and ending on the last day of Shipper’s October billing cycle.
Annual Volume shall mean the estimated transportation volume for the Shipper for a 12-month period, as determined by the Company
Authorized Daily Volume means the volume of gas that Company would transport to or for Shipper on any given day, provided that no interruption has been imposed pursuant to Section 27 of this Part and no curtailment has been imposed pursuant to Section 28 of this Part. The Authorized Daily Volume shall be determined in the manner set forth in Section 26 of this Part.
Billing Month is the period elapsed between consecutive monthly meter readings, whether actual or estimated.
Btu is one (1) British Thermal Unit.
Commercial Customer is a Shipper using gas service through a single meter in commercial activities such as distributing or selling commodities, providing professional services, wholesale and retail stores, offices, office buildings, restaurants, warehouses, railroad and bus stations, banks, laundries, dry cleaners, mortuaries, garages for commercial activity, gasoline stations, theaters, bowling alleys, billiard parlors, bars, grills, taverns, retail bakeries, private hospitals, private schools, churches, religious and charitable institutions, governmental agencies, or similar entities.
Commission means the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission.
Company means Columbia Gas of Kentucky, Inc., the entity who owns, controls, operates and manages facilities used in connection with the distribution or transportation of natural gas service.
Company’s Billing Cycle means the Company’s accounting revenue month.
Day is a period of twenty-four (24) consecutive hours, beginning at 10:00 a.m.
Dekatherm or Dth means one million British thermal units (Btu's).
Delivery Point or Point of Delivery means the point(s) to which the Company transports and delivers gas to or on behalf of the Shipper.
End-User means an Industrial Customer or Commercial Customer using gas in its own business or operations.
FERC means the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission.
Human Needs Customers means residential customers and all customers whose facilities are used for residential dwellings on either a permanent or temporary basis (such as, but not limited to, apartment buildings, correctional institutions, hospitals, nursing homes, hotels, and motels).
Industrial Customer is a Shipper using gas primarily in a process which either involves the extraction of raw materials from the earth, or a change of raw or unfinished materials into another form or product through the application of heat or heat treating, steam agitation, evaporation, baking, extraction, drying, distilling, or similar processes.
KYPSC means the Kentucky Public Service Commission.
Local Market Area means a continuous, physically-interconnected system of Company-owned distribution piping through which the Company provides natural gas service to customers in a discrete geographic area, utilizing one or more common points of delivery from interstate pipeline supplier(s).
Maximum Daily Volume is the greatest volume of gas which Company shall be obligated to transport to or for a Shipper and which Shipper shall be entitled to receive from Company during any one day.
Mcf means one thousand (1,000) cubic feet of gas.
Receipt Point or Point of Receipt means the point(s) at which Shipper delivers gas to the Company for transportation hereunder.
SAACT or State-Approved Adjustment Clause and Tracker Charges means charges under the Company’s Research and Development Rider or SMRP Rider, as approved by the KYPSC.
Shipper means an End-User or Supplier taking gas transportation service under this Statement of Operating Conditions.
Shipper’s Billing Cycle means the monthly period that occurs between monthly meter readings taken by Company for purposes of billing Shipper for gas transportation services provided by the Company.
Shipper’s Facilities means the Shipper’s property, factories, and buildings where natural gas is being consumed or produced.
Supplier means an entity producing or furnishing natural gas or renewable natural gas for the use of others.
TCO means Columbia Gas Transmission, LLC.
Section 2 – Filing and Posting
This Statement of Operating Conditions is on file with FERC and may be accessed under the eTariff section of its website at www.ferc.gov. All gas transportation service provided by the Company shall be in accordance with this Statement of Operating Conditions as approved by FERC, including any amendments or modifications thereto.
Section 3 – Application for Service
Applications for service shall be made through any office of the Company. The application is not complete until the applicant has fulfilled all applicable eligibility requirements and complied with this Statement of Operating Conditions. A separate application or contract may be required for each separate location, in the case of an End-User, and each Receipt Point, in the case of a Supplier. An application for service may be denied if the Company lacks adequate pipeline capacity, market absorption capability, or facilities necessary to provide the requested service.
Section 4 – Access to Premises
Company and its authorized employees shall have free access at all reasonable times to all of the premises in which gas supplied by Company is used or is to be used, and any premises from which natural gas or renewable natural gas is delivered to the Company. Any employee of Company whose duties require entering a Shipper’s premises will wear a distinguishing uniform or other insignia, and/or show a badge or other identification which will verify employment with the Company. Section 5 – Rights-of-Way
5.1 Company Facilities on Shipper’s Property When, in order to serve a Shipper, it is necessary to extend the Company's facilities over or through the Shipper’s property, the Shipper may be required to enter into a right-of-way agreement with the Company in which the Shipper shall grant to the Company all necessary easements or rights-of-way on property owned by the Shipper at no cost to the Company. Any such easement or right of way shall be recorded and shall run with the land. Shipper will be required to save the Company harmless from claims to the easements or rights-of-way granted to the Company pursuant to this Section. 5.2 Procurement by Shipper When, in order to provide gas transportation service to a Shipper, it is necessary to extend the Company’s facilities over or through the property of a third party, the Shipper shall, at a minimum, use its best efforts to assist the Company in acquiring any necessary easements or rights-of-way on property owned by third parties. The Shipper may be required to secure to, and for, the Company, all necessary and convenient easements or rights-of- way and to pay the costs incident thereto. The Shipper shall accept service subject to any limitations or restrictions contained in the easement or right-of-way agreement. Section 6 – Assignment of Contract
The benefits and obligations of any service application or contract shall begin when Company commences to provide gas transportation service. It shall inure to and be binding upon the successors and assigns, survivors, and executors or administrators, as the case may be, of the original parties thereto, respectively, for the full term thereof. However, no application, agreement or contract for service may be assigned or transferred without the written consent or approval of Company.
When the gas transportation service has been disconnected for non-payment of bills or other violation of this Statement of Operating Conditions the service will not be restored at the same location or connected at another location, for the same or related entities under a different contract or name when it appears to the Company that the change of name is a subterfuge designed to defraud or penalize the Company.
Section 7 – Extensions and Construction of New Facilities Service under this Statement of Operating Conditions will normally be provided from the Company’s existing gas distribution system and the Company shall have no obligation to extend its distribution system or construct new facilities to provide such service. If an Applicant requests service hereunder that would require a main extension or other new facilities and the Company is willing and able construct those facilities, it shall first conduct an economic analysis that considers, among other factors, the capital investment required to construct such facilities and the net present value of the anticipated revenues from the Applicant. To the extent that such analysis shows that all or a portion of the required capital investment is not economically justified at the Company’s expense, the Applicant will be required to pay the Company a non-refundable contribution-in-aid-of-construction equal to that portion of the required investment that is not economically justified, or enter into another mutually acceptable arrangement with the Company that ensures that the Company’s remaining customers are not required to subsidize service to the Applicant. Applicant shall also be required to pay the cost of any additional equipment required to provide the requested service, including any equipment necessary to monitor the gas quality of natural gas or renewable natural gas delivered by the Shipper to the Company or prevent harmful substances from entering the gas stream. Section 8 – Protection of Company’s Property
All meters, piping, regulators, monitoring equipment, and other facilities furnished by or at the expense of Company, which may at any time be in or on Shipper’s premises shall, unless otherwise expressly provided herein, be and remain the property of Company. Shipper shall protect such property from loss or damage. Section 9 – Shipper’s Liability
Shipper shall assume responsibility for all piping, appliances, and equipment used in connection with gas transportation service provided hereunder which are not the property of Company. Shipper will protect and save Company harmless from all claims for injury or damage to persons or property occurring on Shipper’s premises or at the Delivery Point occasioned by such gas or gas service and equipment, except where said injury or damage will be shown to have been caused solely by the negligence of Company.
Section 10 – Meter Testing and Measurement of Gas
10.1 Volumetric Measurement Base is one (1) cubic foot of gas at a pressure base of fourteen and seventy-three one-hundredths (14.73) pounds per square inch absolute (thirty (30) inches of mercury), a temperature base of sixty degrees Fahrenheit (60°)(520° F. absolute), and without adjustment for water vapor content.
10.2 Average Absolute Atmospheric (Barometric) Pressure is assumed to be fourteen and four-tenths (14.4) pounds per square inch, irrespective of actual elevation of location of the Delivery Point above sea level or variations in actual barometric pressure from time to time.
10.3 Flowing Temperature. Company shall determine the temperature of the natural gas flowing through the meter or meters by recorder, or as read from established tables for the location involved.
10.4 Specific Gravity of the natural gas shall be determined by Company, or at Shipper’s option by joint test, at the commencement of deliveries and as often as deemed necessary.
10.5 Supercompressibility. The deviation of the gas from the laws for ideal gases shall be determined by Company, or jointly at Shipper’s option, in one of the following ways:
(a) The deviation factors shall be computed by approved methods or read from standard tables, in accordance with Report No. 3 of the Gas Measurement Committee of the American Gas Association, as amended, expanded, or superseded from time to time. Such computations or selection of factors from tables shall be based on the composition of the gas and conditions at point of measurement, and the factors used to be checked by tests of the gas made with such reasonable frequency as found necessary; or
(b) The deviation factors shall be determined by tests of the gas made with such reasonable frequency as found necessary.
10.6 Measuring Equipment. Unless otherwise agreed upon, Company will install, maintain, and operate measuring stations equipped with displacement or flow meters and other necessary measuring equipment by which the volumes of gas transported shall be determined. The gas transported shall be measured in accordance with the latest approved methods in use in the industry generally. Orifice meters shall be installed and operated, and gas volumes computed in a practical and appropriate manner, in accordance with Report No. 3 of the Gas Measurement Committee of the American Gas Association, as amended, expanded, or superseded from time to time. Displacement meter readings shall be adjusted for pressure and temperature conditions. Shipper may install check measuring equipment, provided that such equipment shall be so installed as not to interfere with the operations of Company. Company and Shipper, in the presence of each other, shall have access to the other's measuring equipment at all reasonable times, but the reading, calibrating, and adjusting of Shipper’s check measuring equipment and the changing of charts shall be done only by Shipper unless otherwise agreed upon. Both Company and Shipper shall have the right to be present at the time of any installing, reading, cleaning, changing, repairing, inspecting, testing, calibrating, or adjusting done in connection with the other's measuring equipment. The records from Shipper’s measuring equipment shall remain the property of Shipper, but upon request, each will submit to the other its records and charts, together with calculations, for inspection, subject to return within thirty (30) days after receipt thereof. Company shall exercise reasonable care in the installation, maintenance, and operation of its equipment so as to avoid any inaccuracy in the determination of the volume of gas delivered.
10.7 Calibration and Test of Meters. The accuracy of all measuring equipment shall be verified by the owner at reasonable intervals and, if requested, in the presence of representatives of the other party, but neither Company nor Shipper shall be required to verify the accuracy of such equipment more frequently than once in any thirty (30) day period. If either party at any time desires a special test of any measuring equipment, or if either party at any time observes an error in any such measuring equipment, it will promptly notify the other party, and the parties shall then cooperate to secure a prompt verification of the accuracy of such equipment.
10.8 Correction of Metering Errors. If upon periodic test, request test, or complaint test a meter in service is found to be more than two percent (2%) fast, additional tests shall be made to determine the average error of the meter.
If test results on a meter show an average error greater than two percent (2%) fast or slow, or if a Shipper has been incorrectly billed for any other reason, except in an instance where Company has filed a verified complaint with the appropriate law enforcement agency alleging fraud or theft by Shipper, Company shall immediately determine the period during which the error has existed, and shall recompute and adjust the Shipper’s bill to either provide a refund to Shipper or collect an additional amount of revenue from the underbilled Shipper. Company shall readjust the account based upon the period during which the error is known to have existed. If the period during which the error existed cannot be determined with reasonable precision, the time period shall be estimated using such data as elapsed time since the last meter test, if applicable, and historical transportation volumes for Shipper. If that data is not available, the average transportation volumes of similar Shipper loads shall be used for comparison purposes in calculating the time period. In all instances of Shipper overbilling, Shipper’s account shall be credited or the overbilled amount refunded at the discretion of Shipper within thirty (30) days after the final meter test results. Company shall not require Shipper repayment of any underbilling to be made over a period shorter than a period coextensive with the underbilling.
10.9 Monitoring Usage. Company shall monitor the usage of Shippers who are End-Users at least annually. The procedures shall be designed to draw Company's attention to unusual deviations in Shipper’s usage and shall provide for reasonable means by which Company can determine the reasons for the unusual deviation. If Shipper’s usage is unduly high and the deviation is not otherwise explained, Company shall test Shipper’s meter to determine whether the meter shows an average error greater than two (2) percent fast or slow.
If Company's procedure for monitoring usage indicates that an investigation of Shipper’s usage is necessary, Company shall notify Shipper in writing either during or immediately after the investigation of the reasons for the investigation, and of the findings of the investigation. If knowledge of a serious situation requires more expeditious notice, Company shall notify Shipper by the most expedient means available.
10.10 Shipper Notification. If a meter is tested and it is found necessary to make a refund or back bill Shipper, Shipper shall be notified.
Shipper accounts shall be considered to be current while a dispute is pending pursuant to this section, as long as Shipper continues to make payments for the disputed period in accordance with historic usage, or if that data is not available, the average usage of similar customer loads, and stays current on subsequent bills.
10.11 Failure of Measuring Equipment. In the event any measuring equipment is out of service, or is found registering inaccurately and the error is not determinable by test, previous recordings or deliveries through such equipment shall be estimated:
(a) By using the registration of any check meter or meters if installed and accurately registering, or, in the absence of (a):
(b) By correcting the error if the percentage of error is ascertainable by calibration, special test, or mathematical calculation, or, in the absence of both (a) and (b), then:
(c) By estimating the quantity of transportation volumes based on transportation volumes during periods under similar conditions when the meter was registering accurately.
The estimated readings shall be used in determining the volume of gas transported for any known or agreed-upon applicable period. In case the period is not known or agreed-upon, such estimated deliveries shall be used in determining the volume of gas delivered during the latter half of the period beginning on the date of the immediately preceding test and ending on the date the measuring equipment was adjusted to record accurately; the recordings of the measuring equipment during the first half of said period shall be considered accurate in computing deliveries.
10.12 Preservation of Records.
The complete record of tests of each meter shall be continuous for at least two (2) periodic test periods and shall in no case be less than two (2) years.
10.13 Standard Delivery Pressure
For Shippers who are End-Users, the Company uses seven (7) inches water column as its standard pressure as measured at the outlet of Shipper’s meter.
When conditions warrant, and Shipper and Company mutually agree, certain Shippers may receive gas at pressures higher than the standard pressure. In these cases either indices compensating for the delivery pressure or pressure factors corresponding to delivery pressure will be used to adjust volumes of gas billed.
The above paragraphs notwithstanding Company shall assume no liability from any damage or loss resulting from inadequate or interrupted supply or from any pressure variation when such conditions are not due to willful fault or neglect on its part.
Section 11 – Quality of Gas Delivered to Company 11.1 Quality of Gas at Point(s) of Receipt with an Interstate Pipeline. Gas delivered by or on behalf of Shipper to Company at Receipt Points with an interstate pipeline shall conform to the interstate pipeline’s gas quality standards. 11.2 Quality of Gas at Other Point(s) of Receipt. Gas delivered by or on behalf of Shipper to Company at Receipt Points other than an interstate pipeline shall be commercially free from oil, water, air, salt, dust, gum, gum-forming constituents, harmful or noxious vapors, or other solid or liquid matter which might interfere with its merchantability or cause interference with proper operation of the lines, regulators, meters, and other equipment of Company or its customers. Shipper will indemnify and hold Company harmless from any suits, actions, debts, accounts, damages, costs, losses and expenses, including but not limited to, attorneys' fees and expenses, arising from personal injury, death, or damage to Company's equipment or facilities or arising from personal injuries, death, or damage to the facilities, products, or equipment of Company's other customers or third parties, or arising from additional hours worked by Company or its other customers or third parties, caused as a result of Shipper’s gas failing to meet the quality specifications set forth herein. To assure that the gas delivered by Shipper to Company conforms to the quality specifications of this Section, Shipper’s gas shall be analyzed at the Receipt Point(s) from time-to-time as Company deems necessary. Initial start-up testing may include filter effectiveness analysis. Shipper shall be responsible for all costs associated with acceptable alternatives, including, but not limited to, initial start-up testing.
4. Historical testing and data presented in this Statement include a siloxane detection threshold of <0.5mg Si/m3. Analytical methods have recently been improved resulting in a reduced detection threshold of <0.1mg Si/m3. Due to specific limitations of certain identified applications within an affected zone of influence, Company and Shipper may agree upon a reduced threshold.

In addition, Company and Shipper may agree upon a different specification for halocarbons, provided that (1) Shipper has delivered RNG to Company for a period of at least five years prior to the effective date of this tariff section, and (2) Shipper has demonstrated, to the reasonable satisfaction of Company, that the RNG meeting the agreed-upon specification will not adversely affect (a) the quality of public utility service provided by Company; (b) the operation of Company’s equipment; or (c) the operation of the gas-burning equipment of Company’s customers. As used in the foregoing table, “Btu” means British thermal unit; “scf” means standard cubic foot; “MM” means one million; “CHDP” means cricondentherm hydrocarbon dew point; “ppmv” means parts per million by volume; and “ppbv” means parts per billion by volume. As used herein, renewable natural gas or “RNG” means gas, consistently primarily of methane, which (1) is derived from biogas produced by landfills, animal farms, wastewater treatment plans, or other sources, and (2) is subsequently processed by removing carbon dioxide, nitrogen, and other constituents in order to convert the biogas into pipeline-compatible gaseous fuel. The Total Heating Value of the gas shall be determined by taking samples of the gas at the Receipt Point(s) at such reasonable times as may be designated by Company. The Btu content per cubic foot shall be determined by an accepted type of calorimeter or other suitable instrument for a cubic foot of gas at a temperature of sixty (60) degrees Fahrenheit when saturated with water vapor and at a pressure of 14.73 psia. The Btu determination designated by Company shall be made by Company at its expense. Any additional Btu determinations requested by Shipper shall be at Shipper’s expense. Company may, on a not-unduly discriminatory basis, accept volumes of gas, including renewable natural gas, that fail to meet the quality specifications set forth in this tariff section, if Company determines that it can do so without adversely affecting (1) system operations; (2) the operation of the Company’s equipment; (3) the operation of gas-burning equipment of Company’s other customers; or (4) the quality of public utility service provided by Company. In deciding whether to accept such volumes of gas, the Company shall consider, without limitation, (1) which specifications are not being met; (2) the sensitivity of customer equipment and potential impact on such equipment; (3) Shipper’s plan to improve gas quality; (4) the effect on system supply; (5) interchangeability; (6) the anticipated duration of the quality deviation; and (7) the blending ratio between geological natural gas and RNG in the area of Company’s distribution system where RNG is being injected. Company shall not be obligated to accept gas which it reasonably believes may adversely affect the standard of public utility service offered by Company, or gas which it reasonably believes may adversely affect the operation of its equipment or the gas-burning equipment of its customers. If any gas delivered hereunder fails to meet the quality specifications set forth herein, Company may, at any time, elect to refuse to accept all or any portions of such gas until Shipper brings the gas into conformity with such specifications. 11.3 Gas Quality Testing. Gas delivered to Company must be continuously monitored, at Shipper’s expense, to ensure it meets the quality specifications set forth in Section 11.2. Constituents that are not continuously monitored using currently-available technology must be tested in a laboratory once per year at Company’s expense. If the quality of the gas, based on a laboratory test, does not meet the standards in Section 11.2, the gas must be tested in a laboratory monthly, at the Shipper’s expense, until the gas meets the standards in Section 11.2 for three consecutive months or the Shipper otherwise demonstrates to the Company, in the Company’s reasonable discretion, that it has remediated the constituent deficiency. Such tests shall include only the test method or methods that test for the specific standard or standards that were not met, but Company may consider any results provided by such test method(s). Company will provide Shipper with at least three (3) business days’ notice of the tests described in this Section 11.3, and Shipper will be given the opportunity to be present and observe such tests. Company may, at its option, require Shipper to install automatic shutoff devices, at Shipper’s expense, to prevent gas that fails to meet the quality specifications set forth in Section 11.2 from entering Company’s pipeline system. The scope of all gas testing shall follow the parameters below based on the origin of the gas. The parameters for each origin of gas are based on the source of gas and likelihood of a constituent being present in the source gas. The Company has the discretion to test for additional constituents on the list below, notwithstanding the origin of the gas, if the Company reasonably believes those constituents may be present.

Section 12 – Possession and Control of Gas
After Shipper delivers gas or causes gas to be delivered to Company at the Point(s) of Receipt specified in the Service Agreement, Company shall be deemed to be in control and possession of the gas until thermally equivalent quantities (less retainage) are redelivered to Shipper or for the account of Shipper at the Point(s) of Delivery. Company shall have no responsibility with respect to such gas before Shipper delivers or causes such gas to be delivered to Company or after Company redelivers such gas to or for Shipper, or on account of anything which may be done, happen, or arise with respect to such gas before such delivery or after such redelivery.
Section 13 – Force Majeure
Neither Company nor Shipper shall be liable in damages to the other for any act, omission or circumstance occasioned by or in consequence of any acts of God, strikes, lockouts affecting the company or its suppliers of gas, acts of the public enemy, wars, blockades, insurrections, riots, epidemics, landslides, lightning, earthquakes, fires, storms, floods, washouts, arrests and restraints of rulers and peoples, civil disturbances, explosions, breakage or accident to machinery or lines of pipe, the binding order of any court or governmental authority which has been resisted in good faith by all reasonable legal means, and any other cause, whether of the kind herein enumerated or otherwise, not reasonably within the control of the party claiming suspension and which by the exercise of due diligence such party is unable to prevent or overcome. Failure to prevent or settle any strike or strikes shall not be considered to be a matter within the control of the party claiming suspension.
Such causes or contingencies affecting the performance hereunder by either Company or Shipper, however, shall not relieve it of liability in the event of its concurring negligence or in the event of its failure to use due diligence to remedy the situation and to remove the cause in an adequate manner and with all reasonable dispatch, nor shall such causes or contingencies affecting such performance relieve either party from its obligations to make payments of amounts then due hereunder in respect of gas theretofore transported.
Section 14 – Reconnection of Service
If service is discontinued at the request of any Shipper, Company may refuse service to such Shipper, at the same premises within eight (8) months, unless it shall first receive a payment of the reconnect fee set forth in Part 1, Statement of Currently-Effective Rates.
Company will charge a reconnect fee of twenty dollars ($20) when service has been disconnected for nonpayment of bills or for violation of Company's Rules and Regulations and Shipper has qualified for and requested the service to be reconnected.
Section 15 – Creditworthiness
The Company shall perform a creditworthiness evaluation of the Applicant or Shipper, including an assessment of the credit risk exposure resulting from the rates for services contained in Part 1, Statement of Currently-Effective Rates. The Company shall not be required to initiate or maintain service to any Shipper who is or has become insolvent or who, at the Company’s request, fails within a commercially reasonable time to demonstrate creditworthiness, as determined by the Company in its reasonable discretion.
Section 16 – Billing and Payment
Each month, the Company will render an invoice to Shippers showing the total amount of gas transported during the preceding month and the amount due. When information concerning the volumes transported during a given month is in the control of the Shipper, the Shipper shall furnish such information to the Company on or before the fifth (5th) business day of the following month. Shipper shall pay Company the amount shown on the invoice on or before the due date, which will be at least fifteen (15) days after the date of the invoice.
Section 17 – Late Payment Penalty
A Late Payment Penalty of five percent (5%) may be assessed, only once on any bill for rendered services, if Shipper fails to pay bill by the due date shown on Shipper’s invoice. Any payment received will first be applied to the bill for service rendered. Additional penalty charges shall not be assessed on unpaid penalty charges.
If prior to the due date of payment, Shipper in good faith disputes the bill in part or total, and pays to Company such amounts as it concedes to be correct, and at any time thereafter within ten (10) days of a demand made by Company, furnishes a surety bond in an amount and with surety satisfaction to Company, guaranteeing payment to Company of the amount ultimately found due upon such bills after a final determination which may be reached either by agreement or judgment of the courts, as may be the case, then Company shall not be entitled to suspend further delivery of gas unless and until default be made in the conditions of such bond.
Section 18 – Returned Payment Fee
If Shipper’s payment of a bill for service is returned by a bank as unpaid, Shipper will be charged the Returned Payment Fee set forth in Part 1, Statement of Currently-Effective Rates, to cover the cost of further processing of the account.
Section 19 – Termination
The Company reserves the right to discontinue furnishing gas transportation service to a Shipper with at least ten (10) days written notice from the Company to the Shipper, irrespective of any claim pending against the Company, upon the occurrence of any one of the following events:
A) For non-payment of approved charges;
B) For failure to comply with any of the Company’s Statement of Operating Conditions as filed with the Commission, or with any provision of Shipper’s agreements with the Company.
Notice of discontinuance shall be considered to be given a Shipper when a copy of such notice is left with the Shipper, or left at the premises where Shipper’s bill is rendered, or posted in the United States mail, addressed to the Shipper’s last post office address shown on the records of the Company.
Section 20 – Changes in Contracted Service
Changes in contracted volumes shall be made in any one of the following ways:
A. In the event Shipper shall desire an increase in the then effective contracted volumes, Shipper shall notify Company by April 1, of any year as to the total amount of increase required. If Shipper is advised by Company that it has the required capacity and facilities then Shipper shall execute a contract to become effective November 1, of such year which shall specify the total amount required.
B. In the event Shipper shall desire a decrease in the then effective contracted volumes, after the expiration of the development period, Shipper shall notify Company by April 1, in any year of the desire to decrease to become effective November 1 of such year, provided, however, that if the requested decrease would have increased a contribution-in-aid-of-construction required under Section 7 of this Part, Shipper may be required to pay the difference between the original and increased contribution as a condition for approval of the decrease. Shipper must maintain a minimum contracted volume of 25,000 Mcf per year to remain eligible for gas transportation service hereunder.
C. For changes in effective contracted volumes requested on shorter notice than in A or B above, Company shall, giving consideration to all pertinent factors, use its best efforts to comply with such requests.
Section 21 – Operating Information and Estimates
Upon request of Company, Shipper shall from time to time submit estimates of its daily, monthly and annual transportation volumes, including peak day requirements, together with such other operating data as company may require in order to plan its operations.
Section 22 – Charges for Shipper-Authorized Service
When a Shipper requests the Company's services for premises work, the Company will charge the rates set forth in Part 1, Statement of Currently-Effective Rates. The service performed on the Shipper’s premises will carry a 30 day labor warranty, but on parts and materials, the Company will honor only the manufacturer's warranty. Section 23 – Charges for Shipper-Requested Excess Flow Valves
A Shipper that is an End-User may request installation of an Excess Flow Valve pursuant to Federal Pipeline and Hazardous Materials Safety Administration (“PHMSA”) regulation at 49 C.F.R. § 192.383. All such installations requested by Shipper shall be at the Shipper’s expense in the form of a contribution in aid of construction. The Company will provide Shipper the cost of installation based upon Company’s expected actual total cost. The Company and Shipper will mutually agree upon the timing of such installation subject to any necessary permitting that may be required and consideration of reasonable scheduling of available resources of the Company. In no event shall Company install a Shipper requested Excess Flow Valve if one or more of the following conditions is present: A) Gas deliveries on the line exceed 1,000 standard cubic feet per hour.
B) The service line does not operate at a pressure of 10 psig or greater throughout the year.
C) Company has prior experience with contaminants in the gas stream that could interfere with the Excess Flow Valve’s operation or cause loss of service to a Shipper.
D) The Excess Flow Valve could interfere with necessary operation and maintenance activities, or,
E) An Excess Flow Valve meeting applicable performance standards is not commercially available.
Section 24 – Theft of Service
Company may terminate service to Shipper without advance notice if it has evidence that Shipper has obtained unauthorized service by illegal use or theft. Within twenty-four (24) hours after such termination, Company shall send written notification to Shipper of the reasons for termination or refusal of service upon which Company relies. This right of termination is separate from and in addition to any other legal remedies which Company may pursue for illegal use or theft of service. Company shall not be required to restore service until Shipper has paid for all service acquired through illegal use or theft and provided assurance, to the Company’s reasonable satisfaction, that such conduct will not occur in the future.
Section 25 – Delivery of Shipper-Owned Gas
Subject to the limitations of Company's pipeline capacity in its system and market absorption capability, Company will accept deliveries of Shipper’s gas at the Receipt Point(s), less applicable retainage, for redelivery to Shipper’s facilities or other designated Delivery Point(s), in Mcf. Such gas volumes delivered to Company and redelivered to Shipper shall be limited to the annual and maximum daily transportation volumes for each facility or, at Company's discretion, lesser volumes if Shipper’s expected transportation volumes are projected to be less than stated contract quantities. These volume levels shall represent the actual expected transportation volumes and may be exceeded only with the prior consent of Company. Notwithstanding anything herein to the contrary, in order to support reliable service on Company’s system, Company may require Shipper to utilize other Receipt Point(s) or Delivery Point(s) as designated by Company from time to time.
It is the Shipper’s obligation to deliver sufficient gas supplies to Company at the Receipt Points for redelivery to Shipper’s facilities or other designated Delivery Points(s). If for a period of at least five (5) consecutive days in one billing period, the Company (1) has not received gas supply for Shipper’s account, and (2) the account’s bank balance is insufficient to cover the transportation volumes or the Shipper did not have access to its bank balance due to the Company’s issuance of a Balancing Service Interruption, and (3) the Shipper transported gas on one or more days during such five (5) day period, gas transportation service may be terminated at the end of the billing period.
Section 26 – Authorized Daily Volume
Shipper’s Authorized Daily Volume on any day consists of the Shipper’s transported volumes (as determined herein). Company may, but is not obligated to, transport additional gas volumes that are in excess of the Authorized Daily Volume. These additional daily volumes shall be on a best efforts basis, and will be based on information available to Company. In the event actual transportation volumes are in excess of the Authorized Daily Volume on any day on which the Company requires Shipper to limit gas consumption to that Authorized Daily Volume, Shipper shall be liable for all penalties, fines and charges incurred by Company as a result of Shipper’s transportation volumes in excess of its Authorized Daily Volume.
For Shippers who are End-Users, the portion of Shipper’s Authorized Daily Volume attributable to gas delivered to Company shall consist of two parts. The first part shall consist of volumes delivered at Receipt Points where the upstream transporter, producer, or other delivering entity does not report deliveries to Company on a daily basis. The portion of Shipper’s Authorized Daily Volumes attributable to this part shall be determined by dividing the volume of gas delivered to or for Shipper in the month by the number of days in that month.
The second part shall consist of volumes delivered by upstream transporters which report Shipper’s deliveries to Company on a daily basis. If the upstream transporter’s reporting system is acceptable to Company, Company may, at its option, utilize such system to determine Shipper’s deliveries on any day. If Company elects not to utilize such reporting system, it shall determine Shipper’s deliveries using the best information available, as determined by Company.
For Shippers who are Suppliers, their Authorized Daily Volumes shall consist of volumes delivered directly to the Company within the Local Market Area(s) in which their Delivery Point(s) are located.
Section 27 – Interruption of Gas Transportation Service
Notwithstanding the provisions of Section 26 of this Part, the Company may interrupt gas transportation service provided under this Statement of Operating Conditions in the following situations: A) When either the supply available to the Company or the Company’s system delivery capacity is not sufficient to simultaneously serve all non-firm customer requirements and maintain continuous, safe service to all firm customers;
B) When interruption is necessary in order to perform maintenance or tests or make modifications, repairs, or replacements of the Company’s facilities or the facilities of its upstream suppliers;
C) When the Company is unable to provide service due to events of force majeure, as defined in Section 13 of this Part;
D) When Company transports gas to or for Shipper by displacement and such interruption is necessary to prevent Company from exceeding its contractual limitations with interstate pipeline suppliers, including, but not limited to, any maximum daily delivery obligation (“MDDO”), except that Company will not interrupt deliveries pursuant to this subparagraph unless:
(1) Such interruption is necessary to enable Company to maintain deliveries to high priority customers in the same local market area; or
(2) Company’s interstate pipeline supplier has directed Company to limit its deliveries to the applicable MDDO in order to enable the supplier to maintain firm deliveries on its pipeline system;
E) When it is necessary to interrupt a delivery by displacement due to limited market absorption capability;
F) When interruption is necessary in order for the Company to comply with operational orders issued by one or more of the Company’s pipeline suppliers;
G) When it is necessary to limit deliveries into the Company’s system due to the level of storage inventories or limitations on storage injections or withdrawals and the need for the Company to remain within the operational parameters of the Company’s upstream storage providers and avoid the imposition of monetary penalties or loss of gas supplies; and
H) When gas delivered to the Company’s system fails to meet the gas quality standards set forth in Section 11 of this Part.
On any day when Shipper has been given notice by the Company to interrupt, any quantity of gas transported to the Delivery Point in excess of the quantity specified to be transported for that day shall be subject to the penalty charge set forth in Part 1, Statement of Currently-Effective Rates, for all volumes transported in excess of one hundred three percent (103%) of the amount specified, in addition to the applicable charges for gas transportation service and any fines or penalties incurred by the Company as a result of Shipper’s failure to interrupt.
Shipper shall be liable for any personal injury or damage to the property of Company or third parties which results from Shipper’s failure to interrupt, and Shipper shall indemnify and hold Company harmless with respect to such injuries or damages.
Company shall not be liable for any loss, cost, damage, injury, or expense that may be sustained by Shipper by reason of a partial or complete interruption of gas transportation service in accordance with this Statement of Operating Conditions.
Section 28 – Seasonal Curtailment of Gas Transportation Service
If, in Company's judgment, it is necessary to limit the delivery of natural gas on a monthly or seasonal basis in order (1) to supply market requirements based on gas supply available, or to (2) limit deliveries into the Company’s system on a monthly or seasonal basis due to the level of storage inventories or limitations on storage injections or withdrawals and the need for the Company to remain within the operational parameters of the Company’s upstream storage providers and avoid the imposition of monetary penalties or loss of gas supplies, Company shall curtail or discontinue in whole or in part gas service to its Shippers by giving notice to such Shippers of the level of curtailment required.
Maximum Monthly Volume
A statement showing the applicable Maximum Monthly Volume will be furnished to each Shipper. The Maximum Monthly Volume represents the maximum volume of gas that Company is obligated to deliver to or for Shipper in any one month.
Authorized Monthly Volume
When Shipper’s Maximum Monthly Volume is reduced in accordance with this section, the reduced volume shall thereafter constitute Shipper’s Authorized Monthly Volume and shall continue as Shipper’s Authorized Monthly Volume until changed by notice from Company.
Maximum Seasonal Volume
Shall mean: (1) for the winter season, the total Authorized Monthly Volume for the billing months of November through March, and (2) for the summer season, the total Authorized Monthly Volume for the billing months of April through October.
Availability of Excess Gas
If, in Company’s judgement, it can permit deliveries in addition to the Authorized Monthly Volumes in any month, Company will provide Shippers with as much notice as possible of the availability of such additional volumes.
Penalty Provisions
A. Penalty for Excess Takes at the End of the Five-Month Period Ending with the March Billing Month
If, at the end of the five-month period ending with the March billing month, Shipper’s transportation volumes have exceeded the sum of its Authorized Monthly Volumes for such period, then Shipper shall pay the penalty set forth in Part 1, Statement of Currently-Effective Rates, for all volumes taken in excess of one hundred three percent (103%) of the sum of Shipper’s Authorized Monthly Volumes. Provided, however, to the extent that a Shipper exceeds the sum of its Authorized Monthly Volumes for such period, the penalty shall not apply to any excess volumes authorized pursuant to this section.
B. Penalty for Excess Takes at the End of the Seven-Month Period Ending with the October Billing Month
If, at the end of the seven-month period ending with each October billing month, Shipper’s transportation volumes have exceeded the sum of its Authorized Monthly Volumes for such period, then Shipper shall pay the penalty set forth in Part 1, Statement of Currently-Effective Rates, for all volumes taken in excess of one hundred and two percent (102%) of the sum of Shipper’s Authorized Monthly Volumes, in addition to applicable transportation charges. Provided, however, to the extent that a Shipper exceeds the sum of its Authorized Monthly Volumes for such period, the penalty shall not apply to any excess volumes authorized pursuant to this section.
No Liability for Curtailment, Interruption, or Discontinuance
Company shall not be liable for any loss, cost, damage, injury, or expense that may be sustained by Shipper by reason of partial or complete curtailment, interruption, or discontinuance of gas service in accordance with this Statement of Operating Conditions.
Section 29 – Heat Content Adjustment
When Company receives Shipper’s gas from an interstate pipeline on a dekatherm (one million Btu) basis, Company will make a heat content adjustment in accordance with the procedures set forth below in order to deliver to or for Shipper volumes of gas, in Mcf, equal in heat content to the gas delivered to Company for the account of Shipper. The average monthly heating value of gas measured and calculated by the pipeline which delivers Shipper’s gas to Company will be used each billing month to establish the heating value of the gas delivered by Company to or for Shipper. However, if locally produced gas or gas from pipelines other than the delivering pipeline is introduced into Company's pipeline serving Shipper’s facilities or other designated Delivery Point, so as to raise a question as to the applicability of the heating value determined by the delivering pipeline, either Company or Shipper may request that gas samples be taken to determine the heating value of the gas delivered to or for Shipper at the Delivery Point(s). The following provision will apply in the event either party elects to have gas samples taken:
(A) The party requesting the sample(s) will pay all costs connected with obtaining the sample(s) and having the sample(s) analyzed.
(B) The gas sample(s) shall be obtained at or in the vicinity of Shipper’s facilities or other designated Delivery Point(s) during normal operating hours.
(C) The gas sample(s) will be analyzed at a Company testing facility or at a testing facility approved by Company.
(D) If the analysis is done by an outside testing facility, the testing facility will forward the results directly to Company and Shipper, using a format provided by Company for recording the results of the analysis. If Company performs the analysis, the Company testing facility will forward the results directly to Shipper.
(E) Multiple samples taken during any billing month will be averaged to obtain a Btu value; that Btu value will be applied only for that particular billing month. No retroactive adjustments based on Btu readings obtained in a current billing month will be made to billings for any prior month.
(F) The average Btu value obtained from sample(s) during any billing month shall be used to determine the volumes delivered by Company to or for Shipper only if such Btu value is more than 103% or less than 97% of the saturated (wet) Btu value provided by the delivering pipeline for that month; otherwise the delivering pipeline's Btu value will be used.
Section 30 – Measurement at Points of Receipt with an Interstate Pipeline
When Company receives Shipper’s gas at Point(s) of Receipt with an interstate pipeline, all measurement shall be performed in accordance with the terms of Company's agreement with that interstate pipeline. Section 31 – Warranty of Title
Shipper warrants that it will have good and merchantable title to all natural gas delivered to Company for redelivery to Shipper’s facilities or other designated Delivery Point; that such gas will be free and clear of all liens, encumbrances and claims whatsoever; and that it will indemnify Company and hold it harmless from all suits, actions, debts, accounts, damages, costs, losses, and expenses arising from or out of adverse claims of any and all persons to said gas.
Section 32 – Charges for Third Party Services
If furnishing service to Shipper pursuant to this Statement of Operating Conditions requires Company to use transportation service provided by another entity, any cost incurred by, or billed to Company with regard thereto, shall be billed to Shipper by Company and paid by Shipper. Such costs shall include, without limitation, transportation or delivery charges, retainage for Company use and unaccounted-for gas, filing fees, and penalties incurred as a result of gas volume imbalances or other factors set forth in the applicable rate schedule or contract of such other entity. Shipper shall also reimburse Company for any filing fees paid by Company to another entity when necessary to commence or continue gas transportation service to Shipper.
Section 33 – Delivery Service Agreement
Before commencing service hereunder, Shipper shall execute a service agreement in substantially the form contained within this section. The service agreement shall set forth among other things:
(A) the Point(s) of Receipt at which Company will accept delivery of Shipper’s gas;
(B) the Point(s) of Delivery to which Company will redeliver Shipper’s gas;
(C) Shipper’s maximum daily and annual transportation volumes; and
(D) the specific services and levels of such services for which Shipper has contracted.

PART 3 RATE SCHEDULES
A. Delivery Service (DS) Applicability Entire service area of Company. Availability This rate schedule is available to any Shipper throughout the service area served by Company, except Human Needs Customers, including both End-Users and Suppliers of natural gas or renewable natural gas, provided: (1) Shipper has executed a Delivery Service Agreement with Company; and (2) Shipper has normal annual gas transportation requirements of not less than 25,000 Mcf at any Delivery Point; and (3) Company will not be required to deliver on any day more than the lesser of (1) a quantity of gas equivalent to Shipper’s Maximum Daily Volume specified in its Delivery Service Agreement, (2) the quantity of gas scheduled and confirmed to be delivered into the Company’s distribution facilities on behalf of Shipper on that day, (3) Shipper’s Authorized Daily Volume; or (4) the transportation volume specified by the Company during a period of interruption under Section 27 of Part 2, General Terms and Conditions; and (4) On an annual basis, a Shipper’s Maximum Daily Volume and Annual Transportation Volume will be automatically adjusted to the Shipper’s actual Maximum Daily Volume and actual Annual Transportation Volume based on the Shipper’s highest daily and annual volumetric transportation volumes experienced during the preceding 12-month period ending with March billings. Upon a Shipper’s request, the Company shall have the discretion to further adjust a Shipper’s Maximum Daily Volume and Annual Transportation Volume for good cause shown. Rates The rates for this service, including applicable riders and late payment charges, are set forth in Part 1, Statement of Currently-Effective Rates. Adjustments and Riders Shippers served under this Rate Schedule are subject to the following SAACT charges: Rider for Natural Gas Research and Development Rider SMRP Banking and Balancing Service Shippers taking Banking and Balancing Service are subject to a charge, which reflects the storage cost to the Company to provide a “bank tolerance” to the Shipper of five percent (5%) of the Shipper’s Annual Transportation Volume. The rate for Banking and Balancing Service is set forth in Part 1, Statement of Currently-Effective Rates. Nomination and Scheduling of Transportation Deliveries All transportation deliveries must be nominated and scheduled daily through the Company’s internet-based nomination system. A Shipper taking service under this rate schedule may elect to have nominations submitted by a third-party agent. Daily Measurement All shippers taking service under this rate schedule must have daily measurement.
B. Banking and Balancing Service A. Election
Shippers must subscribe to Banking and Balancing Service, as described in Rate Schedule Delivery Service (DS), to be eligible for the provisions of the service described herein. Shippers without daily metering equipment must subscribe to the Banking and Balancing Service. Daily usage and measurement can be obtained from an electronic meter device, or a charted meter device.
B. Cash-Out
Shippers who have installed daily metering equipment and who choose not to subscribe to Banking and Balancing Service will be placed on a daily cash-out provision, defined as follows. On days when Shipper’s deliveries to the Company are less than its transportation volumes, the Company will sell gas to the Shipper at the higher of: (1) 120% of the average of the Daily Index prices for each day of the applicable month as reported in PLATTS Gas Daily in the Daily price survey section under the heading “Appalachia” for “Columbia Gas, App.” Midpoint, plus the 100% load factor TCO FTS costs (including demand, commodity and retainage); or (2) 120% of the highest commodity purchases by the Company during the calendar month, including the delivered cost of purchases at the city gate, if any, excluding any purchases under fixed price commodity contracts for which the price was determined more than thirty days before the beginning of the calendar month. On days when Shipper’s deliveries to the Company are greater than its transportation volumes, Company may, at its option, purchase the excess deliveries at the lower of: (1) 80% of the average of the Daily Index prices for each day of the applicable month as reported in PLATTS Gas Daily, in the Daily price survey section under the heading “Appalachia” for “Columbia Gas, App.” Midpoint; or (2) 80% of the lowest cost of purchases by the Company during the calendar month, including the delivered cost of purchases at the City Gate, if any, excluding any purchases under fixed price commodity contracts for which the price was determined more than thirty days before the beginning of the calendar month.
C. Volume Bank
Under the Banking and Balancing Service, Company has established a system to account for Shipper’s volumes received by Company but not transported to or for the Shipper during the same monthly billing cycle. Such undelivered volumes shall be called a Volume Bank and Shipper shall be permitted to receive such banked volumes at a later date at Company's discretion. Shipper will use its best efforts to notify Company of a planned or expected significant change in its volume bank level before that change occurs. Shipper may not utilize banked volumes during any period in which an interruption has been imposed pursuant to Section 27 of Part 2, General Terms and Conditions. The availability of Banking and Balancing Service under this Section is contingent upon the policies, practices, and procedures of Company’s interstate pipeline suppliers. Company reserves the right to request Commission approval to modify the banking system, if the policies, practices, procedures of one or more of such interstate pipeline suppliers make it impracticable for Company to continue the Banking and Balancing Service system established herein.
D. Imbalances
The total volume bank of Shipper shall not at any time exceed a ‘bank tolerance’ of five percent (5%) of Shipper’s Annual Transportation Volume. If, at any time, Shipper’s volume bank exceeds the bank tolerance, Company will purchase the excess deliveries at the lower of: (1) 80% of the average of the Daily Index prices for each day of the applicable month as reported in PLATTS Gas Daily publication, in the Daily price survey section under the heading “Appalachia” for “Columbia Gas, App.” Midpoint; or (2) 80% of the lowest cost of purchases by the Company during the calendar month, including the delivered cost of purchases at the City Gate, if any, excluding any purchases under fixed price commodity contracts for which the price was determined more than thirty (30) days before the beginning of the calendar month. In addition, if the Shipper’s exceeded bank tolerance causes the Company to incur a pipeline penalty, Shipper is subject to its proportionate share of any such penalty.
Any volumes of gas that are transported to or for the Shipper in any monthly billing cycle that are in excess of: (A) Shipper’s volume bank from the previous month, plus (B) any volumes delivered to Company by Shipper for that billing cycle, shall be considered a deficiency in deliveries. All deficiencies in deliveries to Company will be billed to the Shipper at the higher of: (1) 120% of the average of the Daily Index prices for each day of the applicable month as reported in the PLATTS Gas Daily publication, in the Daily price survey section under the heading “Appalachia” for “Columbia Gas, App.” Midpoint, plus the 100% load factor TCO FTS costs (including demand, commodity and retainage); or (2) 120% of the highest commodity cost of purchases by the Company during the calendar month, including the delivered cost of purchases at the city gate, if any, excluding any purchases under fixed price commodity contracts for which the price was determined more than thirty days before the beginning of the calendar month.
Company may also, on its own initiative, take such actions as are necessary to (1) immediately bring Shipper’s deliveries to the Company and transportation volumes into balance or (2) reduce Shipper’s volume bank to a level which is equal or less than the bank tolerance permitted under this section. The Company further reserves the right to set limitations prior to, or during the course of a month, on how much gas can be scheduled by the Shipper in an effort to control Shipper’s banking activity.
E. Balancing Service Interruption (“BSI”)
Shippers are subject to Columbia’s issuance of BSIs that will direct Shippers or their Agents to adjust transportation volumes to match confirmed deliveries to the Company, and/or balancing services quantities available from the Company. Failure to comply with a BSI will result in the billing of the following charges to the BSI difference, which is defined as the difference between the actual daily transportation volume and the confirmed supply volume, plus or minus 3%.
(A) Twenty-five dollars ($25) per Mcf times the BSI difference; and
(B) The payment of all other charges incurred by Columbia as a result of Shipper’s noncompliance on the date of the BSI difference.
F. Monthly Bank Transfers
Monthly bank transfers will be permitted between one Shipper/Agent (“transferor”) and another Shipper/Agent (“transferee”) located within the same TCO Market Area and having confirmed deliveries on the same transmission pipeline. Transfers may also be permitted, at the discretion of the Company, between a transferor and a transferee located in different TCO Market Areas and having confirmed deliveries on the same transmission pipeline. All such transfers may only be requested once a month to be effective for the upcoming billing cycle and must be requested within three (3) business days after the conclusion of the Shippers’ monthly billing cycle.
G. Termination of Service
In the event service hereunder is terminated, Company will deliver to Shipper volumes of Shipper’s gas which Company is holding pursuant to this Volume Bank section during the three monthly billing cycles following the date of termination. However, should Shipper fail to take delivery of its entire Volume Bank within the three-month period, Company may, at its option, retain and purchase the undelivered banked volumes. In addition, if Shipper owes Company any outstanding gas transportation charges, or other charges which are due, Company may, at its option, offset said unpaid charges by retaining as necessary, banked volumes that would have otherwise been delivered to Shipper upon termination of service. The value assigned to such retained bank volumes which are purchased or retained will be the cost of Company's least expensive gas supply at the time the gas was delivered to Company.
